content.text: Auto.fun, a token launchpad platform, was recently released with mixed reception. While some team members claimed it was "successful on all metrics," others noted it failed to attract significant attention. The platform primarily focuses on AI features for generating images and content creation, with plans to expand to more "agentic" features in V2, positioning itself as a simpler way to launch agents and tokens.

Several technical issues emerged following the launch. Many users reported problems with early token migrations, with tokens being "locked" or inaccessible. The development team acknowledged an indexing issue affecting tokens created during the initial launch and worked to manually resolve these cases. The platform was temporarily put into maintenance mode for updates to address these and other bugs.

There was significant discussion about whether AI16z is the native token for Auto.fun. Some users expressed skepticism about its value proposition, noting that "Anyone can access @autodotfun completely without having AI16z token" and questioning whether it adds significant value. Others suggested that ElizaOS V2 might revitalize interest in AI16z.

A security incident occurred when Shaw's account was reportedly compromised, leading to the promotion of a suspicious token called "COO" on Pump.fun. Team members confirmed the breach and warned users not to engage with this token.

Despite these challenges, the development team remained active in addressing user concerns, with team members like esk3nder, accelxr, and k_carv responding to issues and providing updates. They emphasized that new token creations should work properly, with problems limited to early tokens, and mentioned that launch partners would be announced once the platform stabilized.

categories.title: Auto.fun Platform Technical Issues and Development Status

content.text: Auto.fun is a recently launched token creation and trading platform on Solana that experienced several technical issues during its initial release. The platform allows users to create and trade tokens with a bonding curve mechanism that transitions to trading pools once certain thresholds are reached.

## Key Technical Issues

1. **Indexing errors** affecting early token creations, preventing users from trading tokens created during launch
2. **Migration issues** where tokens that reached bonding thresholds (85 SOL) weren't properly migrated to trading pools
3. **Jupiter integration errors** with decimal precision causing "error fetching swap amount from jupiter"
4. **UI/UX problems** including incorrect market cap displays, bonding percentage calculation issues, and infinite scroll implementation breaking footer access
5. **Fee claiming functionality** failing with "failed to claim fees" errors
6. **Developer contract confusion** where some users created tokens using leaked developer links before official launch

## Platform Status

The development team put the site into maintenance mode to implement fixes and optimizations. They've been manually fixing individual tokens with indexing issues and addressing broader system problems. According to team members, they've resolved approximately 90% of the reported issues.

The platform operates with a 90/10 fee split structure between token creators and the platform. Post-bonding, token creators can claim fees from LP, receiving a combination of their created token and SOL.

## Future Plans

The team is preparing for a "next phase" with launch partners like com3 and Fractal once stability issues are resolved. They plan to announce partnerships after platform upgrades are completed and implement features based on user feedback. There are also several feature requests from users, including the ability to include website info on token pages, making auto.fun links embed token pictures when shared, and adding multiple parameter sorting options.

categories.title: Auto.fun Platform Launch and Technical Issues

content.text: Auto.fun, a token creation and trading platform on Solana, recently launched with initial success but encountered several technical issues. The platform allows users to create tokens and establish liquidity pools, with a 90/10 fee split between creators and the platform (for AI16z buybacks).

Major technical issues included indexing errors affecting early token creations, migration problems for tokens that reached bonding thresholds, Jupiter integration errors with decimal precision, and claim fee button malfunctions. The development team (including accelxr and k_carv) actively responded to user concerns and manually fixed several affected tokens.

The platform was temporarily put into maintenance mode to implement fixes and optimizations before proceeding with marketing activities and launch partners. The team indicated that tokens require 85 SOL in the bonding curve to migrate, and they're working on UI enhancements to make processes like fee claiming clearer.

There was also discussion about ElizaOS implementation challenges, particularly regarding database connectivity with PostgreSQL and custom LLM integration. Users reported Content Security Policy (CSP) issues when running ElizaOS on Windows machines and asked about plugin functionality for image generation and MIDI communication.

The team mentioned upcoming ElizaOS V2 capabilities, particularly regarding API calls and file reading from external sources. Some users experienced issues with temperature settings not affecting agent behavior despite configuration changes. The development team shared documentation links and suggested GitHub issue submissions for unresolved problems.
